posts.content:
One of the easiest ways to make more money as an employee: 
Go to your boss and ask for less money. 

Here's how it works.

Any employee who can directly tie what they do to what the company makes can then make the following statement: "Hey, instead of giving me a $100,000 base salary, I would like a $50,000 base salary. However, my bonus will be directly tied to the company's yearly success."

That way you are shifting the risk from the business owner to yourself. Whenever you take on more risk in life, you will be entitled to more reward.

IF and only IF you know for a FACT that you are exceptional at what you do... ask to get paid less.

â€“ The SDR or sales manager to self-analyze.
â€“ An item to discuss during weekly or monthly deal reviews.

The key focus of validation?

Double-check the customer still fits your ICP.

Itâ€™s overlooked because:
â€“ The SDR wants to hit quota.
â€“ The sales manager wants to hit quota.
â€“ Or simply, the revenue is too tempting to resist.

But if youâ€™re serious about scaling to 8 or 9 figures, you must take this step.

You must reconsider going ahead if the ICP isnâ€™t the right fit.

Hereâ€™s whyâ€¦

I recently read a story from Jake Fuentes, co-founder of Cascade, about why he shut his startup down.

He admitted that â€œICP frayâ€ was a key factor.

Cascade initially defined their ICP as â€œnontechnical business analysts using Excel to crunch big data setsâ€.

The definition was too broad.

They ended up chasing customers with wildly different use cases:
â€“ A scooter company managing location data.
â€“ An HR team managing employee data.

They didnâ€™t have a framework to accept or reject opportunities, so they tried to support them all.

What's the difference between sympathy and empathy?

The tragic fires in LA have had me reflecting deeply on this.

Iâ€™ve received so many thoughtful messages checking in, and Iâ€™m incredibly grateful for them.

They remind me how much people care and I can't overstate how much they meant to me.

They also got me thinking about the difference between sympathy and empathyâ€”and what it takes to turn empathy into meaningful action.

It reminded me of Edith Stein, a philosopher who lived in Germany during WWII and whose work on empathy led her to be canonized as a saint by Pope John Paul II.

Stein outlined three levels of empathy:

â€¢ Cognitive empathy: Understanding what someone is experiencing.
â€¢ Emotional empathy: Trying to feel what they feel.
â€¢ Compassionate empathy: Taking action to support them.

The third level suggests itâ€™s not enough to ask â€˜how can I helpâ€™?

You must actually offer a helping hand.

In line with that spirit, Iâ€™d like to offer a free seat at our next cohort which launches at the end of the month to anyone who has been displaced by the fires.

In times of crisis, you look to your network.

And although this doesnâ€™t solve your immediate problemsâ€¦

If it helps you in rebuilding, then weâ€™re more than happy to have you join and learn alongside the BC community.

In the beginning the goal of being on LinkedIn is to find work.

Then the goal becomes to grow and build a business, while helping others.

In an odd twist of fate, the final goal of posting on LinkedIn is to get to the place where you never *have to* log in again.

You will know some of your best follows have *made it* when they disappear.

Have you ever blown your own mind by doing the things that you never imagined were possible? 

That is what it is like to be on a healing journey â€” there are myriad times in the day when I celebrate a Sic Parvis Magna Momentâ„¢ï¸ (greatness from small beginnings) for myself, & illuminate them for others.

Iâ€™ve been trying to make mornings happen since birth. Iâ€™ve never understood â€˜morning peopleâ€™ who jump out of bed ready for the day without the aid of 64 alarms and 74 cups of coffee. BUT Iâ€™ve always said with truth in jest, if I were a morning person Iâ€™d be rich & skinny.

As it turns out, 2024 was the year that I made mornings happen in a profound way. Donâ€™t get me wrong, I still LOVE sleep.

As Iâ€™ve been scaling this business over the last 18+ months, Iâ€™ve had a really, really hard time navigating somatic responses to extreme stress.

If you know me, you know that I GSD! Working SO hard over the past 20+ years to build other peopleâ€™s organizations â€” only in vain to lose my job to yet another RIF. But when I needed to put that same intensity into my own venture my body forced me to rest. And it's made me feel absolutely hopeless.

When I lost my job in June 2023, I was still in the early stages of coming out of lifelong survival mode. Learning how-to-human at almost 40 presents a significant level of challenges, especially when youâ€™re used to working beyond your capacity. Actually, I didnâ€™t even know I had a capacity before 2022.; I thought I was a workhorse machine, only resting at the point of depletion.

Finding balance in my life has been elusive, but I knew that I needed to get into a schedule to manage my migraines more effectively to achieve success/not lose my mind.

If I wanted different results, I must do the things Iâ€™ve never done before.

And so I began 7AM CrossFit. [6:30 AM a$$ in seat for a ride requires me to stop working before 3 AM - so itâ€™s a win all around]

It took me from June until September to really get into a groove. In June I was still groggy & grumpy, but by September I was LOVING it, networking the F out of the morning, meeting more people before 8AM than most do all day.

Healing is a just another word for finding new, healthy ways to solve for old problems. Trauma is just another word for extreme, overwhelming stress.

Last Thursday, marked my momâ€™s 6 year death anniversary - a day that used to be a glaring reminder of loss has become a celebration of life & mind/ body/soul wellness that I work SO DANG hard to achieve er'day. I started 1/9 with 7AM CrossFit, recorded a podcast, promoted my affiliate partnerships, staying the course in her honor.

Iâ€™ve always been a sunset chaser, but now I live for the sunrises over the Hudson. Healing = Freedomâ„¢ï¸ from the lies we tell ourselves, a journey as brutal as it is beautiful.

I ran into a friend I haven't seen in a while, after spending some time together, she said 'WOW, you really changed your WHOLE life!'

And if I can do it, anyone can!
